  "market_context": "NQ 5-minute chart on 11 Dec 2023 around the New York open. Price rallied off the 09:30 open, formed buy-side liquidity above intraday highs near 16385, and swept those buy stops before producing a down-close candle through the prior up-close series.",
  "key_observation": "The pattern appeared to be a textbook bearish order block (sweep of buy-side liquidity + displacement close below up-close candles), but it formed in the absence of a higher time frame PD array — the swept highs were only equal highs, not a meaningful POI.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Identified buy-side liquidity resting above the intraday swing highs on the NQ 5-minute chart.",
    "Observed price sweep those buy stops, then waited for a displacement close below the series of up-close candles to validate a bearish order block.",
    "Took the entry on the retest of the order block, placing stop above the sweep high and targeting 2R.",
    "Trade got tagged in and immediately stopped out.",
    "Post-mortem: zoomed out to the 1-hour chart to check for a higher time frame level at the swept highs — found none, only equal highs.",
    "Concluded that without an HTF PD array, the 5-minute up-close candles were just a retracement within a larger move higher, not a valid order block.",
    "Reframed the setup: noted that the actual HTF POI was an hourly fair value gap above, meaning price should be sought higher into that FVG instead."
  ],
  "outcome": "Stopped out — trade was a loss because the order block lacked a valid higher time frame point of interest.",
  "lessons": "An order block is only valid when formed off a higher time frame PD array or important level. The same candle pattern at a random location (e.g. equal highs without HTF context) is not a tradable order block — POI validation is mandatory before entry.",
